# Media Stack

A segmented media automation and delivery platform built around separate acquisition workflows, shared libraries, and dual playback platforms.

> Emby is the primary playback platform. Jellyfin is the secondary platform.
> Remote access is handled through Tailscale only.

---

# At a Glance

| Area | Current Design |
|:--|:--|
| Primary playback | Emby |
| Secondary playback | Jellyfin |
| Shared libraries | Yes |
| Public exposure | None |
| Remote access | Tailscale only |
| Automation style | Segmented Sonarr/Radarr + import lists |
| Standards influence | Trash Guides |

---

# Core Platforms

| Service | Role | Notes |
|:--|:--|:--|
| Emby | Primary media server | Main day-to-day playback platform |
| Jellyfin | Secondary media server | FOSS-first alternate interface using the same libraries |
| Plex | Retired | No longer used due to platform direction and preference for more self-hosted-first options |

---

# Segmented Automation

The automation layer is intentionally split to keep workflows cleaner and better scoped.

| Service Group | Purpose |
|:--|:--|
| Sonarr | General TV |
| Sonarr Anime | Anime-focused TV workflows |
| Sonarr Kids | Kids-focused TV workflows |
| Radarr | General movies |
| Radarr Anime | Anime movie workflows |
| Radarr Kids | Kids movie workflows |

This separation improves:
- library hygiene
- automation clarity
- safer content boundaries
- easier long-term maintenance

---

# Import Lists

Import lists are used to automate discovery and reduce manual adds.

Examples currently used in the stack include:
- streaming TV lists
- Trakt-based imports
- anime lists
- curated movie-user lists
- specialty collection lists such as Studio Ghibli

Trash Guides is an important influence here, especially for keeping automation logic more standardized and maintainable over time.

